snippet.textDisplay:
3:03 Ion Mihai Pacepa (b. October 28, 1928, Bucharest) was Deputy Head of the Department of Foreign Intelligence (espionage) of Communist Romania and personal advisor to President Nicolae Ceausescu. In 1978 he applied for political asylum in the United States, where he worked for the US intelligence community in various operations against the former Soviet bloc. The US government described Pacepa's work as "an important and unique contribution to the United States", Pacepa is a US citizen and now lives in the US.

The conclusion of the report of the Presidential Commission for the Analysis of the Communist Dictatorship in Romania (page 628), approved by the President of Romania and published on December 18, 2006, underlines "the exceptional role played in the unmasking of the criminal nature of the regime and of the Security" by General Pacepa. According to this report, he "it contributed to the dramatic degradation of Ceausescu's image." The information provided by Pacepa was also an important revealer of the criminal character of the dictatorship in influential political and media circles in the West. Security and his heirs never forgave IM Peace to this act of treason. "
